COMMIT GUIDE
============

Purpose
- Keep commit history readable and reviewable.
- Describe intent, not implementation details.

Rules
1) One concern per commit.
2) Commit message describes outcome and intent.
3) Do not include function names, variable names, or file paths in the subject.
4) Do not include tooling or agent references in commit text.
5) Do not include "Co-authored-by" trailers.
6) Keep wording concise, plain, and ASCII-only.

Message style
- Subject should be short and action-oriented.
- Prefer product/behavior framing over code internals.
- Optional body may explain why the change was needed and user impact.
- Brief high-level bullets in the body are good when a commit has a few related concerns.
- Keep those bullets short, useful for someone scrolling history, and light on technical detail.
- Use bullets sparingly.

Good subject examples
- feat(voice): improve state-aware command routing
- fix(api): harden request validation for audio payloads
- docs(frontend): simplify websocket integration flow
- test(voice): expand websocket state transition coverage

Example with body bullets
- Subject: docs(project): update BOM for dual-ToF chamber sizing
- Body:
  - Document active chamber-sizing concept shift to dual rear-wall ToF
  - Note that BOM.xlsx row is pending hardware reception
  - Add timing-stage purchasing guidance and part categories

Avoid
- "update process_ask_query in src/visual_memory/api/routes/ask.py"
- "agent-generated changes"
- "Co-authored-by: ..."
